  <a href="#0" id="0">
   Automatically detecting verbal irony (roughly, sarcasm) is a challenging task because ironists say something other than and often opposite to what they actually mean.
  </a>
  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Discerning ironic intent exclusively from the words and syntax comprising texts (e.g.,, tweets, forum posts) is therefore not always possible additional contextual information about the speaker and/or the topic at hand is often necessary.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   We introduce a new corpus that provides empirical evidence for this claim.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   We show that annotators frequently require context to make judgements concerning ironic intent, and that machine learning approaches tend to misclassify those same comments for which annotators required additional context.
  </a>
